body:
## Steps to reproduce the issue

Consider the following VHDL test case:

```vhdl
library ieee;
use ieee.std_logic_1164.all;

entity tst is
  port (
    i_clk    : In   std_logic;
    i_val    : In   std_logic;
    o_val    : out  std_logic);
end entity tst;

architecture implementation of tst is
	signal	w_val : std_logic := '0';
	signal	r_val : std_logic := '1';
begin

	w_val <= r_val;

	process(i_clk)
	begin
		if (i_clk'event and i_clk = '1') then
			r_val <= i_val;
		end if;
	end process;

	o_val <= w_val;

end architecture;
```

processed with the following SBY script,

```
[options]
mode prove
depth 5

[engines]
smtbmc

[script]
read -vhdl tst.vhd
prep -top tst

[files]
tst.vhd
```

Notice in this construct that contradictory initial values are given to w_val.

## Expected behavior

I understand this is a common VHDL coding style.  Looking through a popular vendor's code, I'm seeing many examples of it.  I am not expecting this to generate a warmup failure, but rather for the initial value to be ignored when overridden by a combinatorial assignment.

## Actual behavior

Warmup failure.

